					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    A Complete Beginners Guide To Necromancers (Levels 1-4)</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:">Zarriah, Dark Elf Necromancer</a> | 
		            10/16/2001 4:05:07 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Necromancers by many are considered very fun characters to play. I myself, love my necromancer. He levels faster than any other character I've ever made, and he can solo very, very well. For all of you out there that are interested in starting up your own necromancer, I write this guide from the beginning. Although some people might say that only experienced people should start play this class, my first character was a necromancer and turned out to be very easy, infact. This guide is meant to start from the beginning, for people who dont like to beg for money and want to play a necromancer with dignity. I hope the following can truly help you to level your necromancer as quickly as possible.<BR>
<BR>
Level 1-<BR>
     Ahh, the beginning. This is a very fun time for your character, as you gain experience very fast, and at the same time don't lose any experience for dying. And, on top of that, when you die you get all of your food back. Before even starting your character, I strongly suggest that you get a map of the following zones, if possible: Neriak Foreign Quarter, Neriak Commons, Neriak Third Gate, Nektulos Forest, East Common Lands, and West Common Lands. These maps can be used in conjuction with the /loc command to navigate. When you start, you will be right in front of a waterfall, with a picture of a giant eye floating on top of the hill onto which the water falls upon. If you turn you your left and your right, you will see to ways to go. The left passage takes you to the clerics guild and to the Neriak Commons. To the right path as an assortment of buildings, including the necromancer and shadow knights guild. Currently, you are in Neriak East Gate, so use the map if you have one to find the guild. If you do not have a map, ask around where the guild is. Most of the time there are other people in the third gate. Once at your guild, locate your guild master by right clicking on your tatterd note once. Turn in your note to him. You should also spend your practice points. To do this, right click on him. Because you are a necromancer, your most used school of magic, not only now but in your future, is Alteration, which is mainly damage over time spells. You should also train in evoking, which is mainly direct damage spells and conjuration, which are spells that summon thing. You should also spend a point in your weapon skill, which is peircing (your staring weapon is a peircing weapon as its a daggar). As you don't have any money at the current moment, you will not be able to afford any spells. So, just leave Third Gate into the Commons. From there, move on to Foreign Quarter. In the north of Foreign Quarter, you can zone into the Nektulos Forest, which is your newbie area. Once into the forest, sit down by one of the guards and begin scribing your two spells, Life Tap and Minor Sheilding. Once scribed, memorize them into your spell jem slots. Stand up and walk out abit, looking for small animals to kill. At this point, anything can kill you, so consider everything that you attack. I would suggest attacking the following: decaying skeletons, black wolves and spiderlings. But, you must be careful about spiderlings; they are social and so will help others of their species if they one attacked. Continue killing these and healing up until level 2.<BR>
<BR>
Level 2-<BR>
     Level 2, as with level 1, is very easy. The only difference is that you will find you die less and you gain a bit less experience. At this point you should have accumulated enough money to buy some of your level 1 spells. I highly reccomend buying the following spells, as they will be very useful: Cavorting Bones, Disease Cloud, Locate Corpse, and Siphon Strength. All of these spells can be purchased from a female merchant in one of the back rooms in the necromancer and shadow knight guild. At level two, these spells are basically the bare minimum. If you do not have enough money, don't despair: continue hunting until you get enough. The total cost for these spells will be approxametely 5 gold, although you may be able to buy them for less. The first spell on the list, Cavorting Bones, is your very first pet spell. Before casting it, you will need to have at least one bone chip. Your pet will be able to attack for you will you blast away at the opponent with your spells. The next spell, disease cloud, is also very useful as it is an excellent DoT (damage over time) spell. It also stops the opponent from gaining their health points back, which is useful in some situations. The next spell, Locate Corpse, is very useful and you will most likely use it for the rest of your life as a necromancer. When you target yourself (by pressing F1) and cast this spell, you will automatically point in the direction of your closest corpse in the zone. This can also be cast on friends or other people by selecting them and casting. The final important spell is Siphon Strength. This does two important things. First, it decreases the opponents strength, causing it to do less damage per hit. Secondly, it gives you the taken strength, which can give you added power to assist your pet with. With added strength, you can also carry more items. If you have enough money left over, i suggest buying these spells: Invisibility Versus Undead and Sense The Dead. The first of these spells will cause you to go invisible to any undead (skeletons, zombies, mummies, and such) for a certain period of time. This becomes useful when traveling because undead will not see you and thus will not get aggrivated on you. The second spell, Sense The Dead, will cause you to automatically turn to the closest undead creature. This will decrease the amount of time it takes for you to find some good things to hunt by automatically finding them for you. At this point, you should start fighting at what many people dub the &quot;Newbie Log&quot;. If you have a map, it can be found near the coordinates +1800, -500. If you do not have a map, as around if someone can lead you to it. The newbie area has many creatures to fight, including an array of spiderlings and black wolves that are usually constant in the area. Fight with your pet so that it doesnt die, and you should advance to level 3 in no time.<BR>
<BR>
Level 3-<BR>
     Level three for me was hard, as my pet was very low level (always 1), so you will need to help your pet when fighting something to keep it alive. At this point, it is reccomended that you fight mainly fire beetles. They usually drop one or two fire beetle eyes, which is good loot and will get you money for your level 4 spells. If you would like to gain experience very fast, join a group of two people, preferrably a shadow knight of a warrior, and fight skeletons (not decaying skeletons) and shadow wolves if you spot any. Skeletons usually drop weapons, which can be given to your pet to do increased damage. If you are looking for even more experience gain with an increase in risk, you can try heading out to the East Commonlands, although I do not very much support it as the East Commonlands are known to have a lot of lag. Continue killing creatures that con black to you (or, in a group, yellow) and level 4 should not be too far away. Also, make sure that you continue to spend your practice points at the guild in Alteration, Evocation, Conjuration, and whatever skill weapon your using.<BR>
<BR>
Level 4-<BR>
     This is one of the best newbie levels. At this level, you are finally able to meditate. This means that memorization of your spells will go by much faster. But, before you can start meditation, you have to spend at least one point in it at your guild. Also, spend points in your most used schools of magic. Do not worry about your weapon, as you will not be using it very often at all. Also, you get your next set of spells. There are many spells you will need, so make sure you have enough money. Go to the back vendor from which you bought your level 1 spells from and buy the following spells if you are financially able: Leering Corpse, Poison Bolt, Lifespike, Gate, Fear, and Clinging Darkness. Leering Corpse is your next pet spell. It is much more powerful than your last pet spell, and you will be able to have it do more damage for you. The only bad thing is that now that you have a better pet, it will now cost two bone chips instead of one. But the extra bone chip more than makes up due to the highly increased amount of damage. Poison Bolt is also important. Poison Bolt will deal a certain amount of staring damage, will poison the animal, and will continually do damage over time. Use it often when fighting creatures. Lifespike is the next spell. Basically, Lifespike is like an upgraded version of your Lifetap spell. It will do more damage and give you more health than Lifetap. Use it often when meleeing an opponent to help your pet. Gate: possibly one of the most important spells in the game. This spell will save your life most of the time; it did for me. Gate will teleport you to your bind point, which is the spot you ressurect when you die. Anytime you get in trouble, such as being low on health, gate is your escape route. Use it wisely, as it consumes a large amount of mana and it might be interrupted due to a long casting time. Next is fear, a really good spell in my opinion. Fear generally has two function. First, it can be used at times when you are being attacked and want the attacker to stop. It can also be used in a technique called &quot;reverse kiting&quot;. This is where the creature has fear casted on it while you and your pet chase it, casting spells on it. The only consequence that I found out about this is that if the opponent ventures anywhere close to creatures of the same species they will help out and you will be bogged with creatures to the point that death is assured. However, this effect does not work with non-social creatures, such as snakes, who dont care if you kill another of your kind. And finally, Clinging Darkness. This spell should almost always be used as your pulling spell, as it slows down the creature considerably (20%) and will do some damage. If you have enough money, you should buy any other level 4 spells you can afford. So, as a level 4 necromancer, here should be your plan of action: first, cast clinging darkness, then poison bolt, have your pet attack it, then cast disease cloud, go in to melee, cast lifespike occasionally when any of your health gets lost. At this point, it is not nessesary to group if you are a responsible person and can take care of your pet well. It is reccomended not to fight spiderlings and decaying skeletons, except if you are collecting bone chips, and to instead mainly fight skeletons and black bears. If you can find a group, I reccomend going to the wizard teleport in the Nektulos forest as it spawns a few skeletons that can be killed to gain a lot of experience.<BR>
<BR>
I really hope that this guide could aid you, especially if you are new to Dark Elves, or even to the game, in playing a succesful and fun necromancer.<BR>
<BR>
Zarriah<BR>
Level 7 Necromancer<BR>
The Vazaelle Server
